6. Hackathon Winning Strategy
The judges will score on Explainability and Indian Context Sensitivity above all else. Here is how to dominate
each evaluation criterion:
Extraction Accuracy
✓ Use Azure Document Intelligence (not raw Tesseract) for scanned PDFs — it handles low-DPI and
mixed-language documents better
✓ Test with actual GSTR-3B and bank statement PDFs before the hackathon — format quirks will surprise you
✓ Add a confidence score to every extracted field — judges appreciate humility
Research Depth
✓ Hard-code MCA21 scraping — most teams will skip this; it's an easy differentiator
✓ Add e-Courts / NJDG lookup by company CIN and promoter PAN (if available)
✓ Show a 'research provenance' log — list every source the agent checked, even null results
Explainability
✓ Embed a SHAP waterfall chart in the CAM — visual impact is significant
✓ Every scored factor should have a plain-English reason (not just a number)
✓ Include a 'decision audit trail' section in the memo showing every data point used
Indian Context Sensitivity
✓ Explicitly call out GSTR-2A vs 3B reconciliation logic in your demo
✓ Name-check CIBIL CMR / CCR in the Character section of the CAM
✓ Show that your OCR handles Devanagari headers gracefully (even if just via detection + skip)
✓ Include RBI NBFC circular lookup if the borrower is an NBFC — big bonus points
Pro tip: Build a live demo where the judge can type a company name and watch the agents run in real
time — news agent fetching articles, MCA agent checking filings, then the CAM downloading as a Word
file. The visual drama of a working pipeline wins hackathons more reliably than a perfect model score.